Metal plates were implanted onto the skull of mice prior to behavioral experiments. Following 2 hours of dark adaption, unanaesthetized mice (over 50 days old) were head-fixed through metal plates under infrared illumination. Light stimuli were provided by an ultra violet LED (peaked at 395 nm), as well as green LED (peaked at around 560 nm), to one eye, while a near-infrared camera (JAI, Denmark) recorded the response from the same eye. Light intensities were measured at the cornea using an optical power meter (Thorlabs, USA). Each session was recorded at 62 Hz frame rate for 1 minute, starting 5 s before a 20 s light stimulus. Pupil areas were measured using ImageJ (NIH, USA). Percentage of pupil constrictions was calculated as 1-amina0×100%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
